Hi, Bill.

As Bill wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/11/2004 at 12:46:56 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>We learned the line x=4 is a vertical line with an x intercept but 
no
>y intercept (never crosses y axis).  Is the line x=0 the only 
>vertical line that has a y intercept since it crosses the origin?
>
>[Difficulty]
>
>
>[Thoughts]
>I think it is since the line crosses the y axis at y=0. Conversly 
>then the line y =0 would be the only horizontal line with an x 
>intercept. Correct?

Actually, the line x=0 never CROSSES the y-axis; it IS the y-axis! 
That is, EVERY point on the line is on the y-axis, so if there is an 
intercept, it is at every point on the line. When every point is an 
intercept, you can't really say that any point is. So not vertical 
line has a y-intercept.

If you have any further questions, feel free to write back.


